<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-327-445  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 327 445.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Feb 5 1990 v24 n6 p8(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Suspect arrested in AIDS disk fraud case. (Joseph Lewis Popp)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Alexander, Michael.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Federal Bureau of Investigation arrests Joseph Lewis Popp,allegedly the author of an 'AIDS Information IntroductoryDiskette.' The diskette, mailed to thousands of MSDOS users inEurope, Africa and Australia, contained a Trojan horse that movedfiles stores on hard disks into hidden directories and encryptedothers.andP;  The disk package had a warning that the program wouldadversely affect other programs on the user's microcomputer harddisk drive unless he pays a fee of $398.andP;  Between 23,000 and27,000 of the disks are estimated to have been mailed.andP;  Popp isaccused of blackmail and extortion under English law.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer industrySoftware ProtectionSoftware packagesFile ManagementComputer CrimesFraudLegal Issues.andO;Person:    Popp, Joseph Lewis, Jr. (cases).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>